narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: I learned multivariable calculus, taking partial derivatives, understanding 3d objects and various theorems.

I really enjoyed the concepts that we learned, and feel like I would be confident tackling most calculus problems I could possibly encounter in life and in my career as a result of my study. I also determined through this course that while the math department outlines strict and understandable guidelines for introductory courses like these, the actual implementation of these course schedules seems unreasonable. For example, we had to submit an extra problem set early the week of each midterm, which put a lot of stress on me and prevented me from going to the review sessions, which were on the same nights that the bonus problem sets were due.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: The classroom sizes are very small which is helpful.
This course is taught by grad students
The course is taught too fast for the amount of content that it contains. Professor was unclear about when to use which theorem

The strength of this course for me was my professor and section. I didn't like the video delivery style of material in this course, and the homework questions were much too difficult, often times trying to trick you. There also was not very good feedback on where I had gone wrong on problem sets, and I eventually gave up trying to correct my work because no answer keys were provided and the Gradescope comments were often vague and confusing. Ultimately, I had a very negative experience with this course.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: I think the course is organized well even though I did not do well in it.
Yes, most STEM majors will require this
I would only recommend this course if the student needs it for the major, otherwise no.
No. Do not take this course unless you absolutely have to, and unless you absolutely kill it on the first midterm and have complete confidence in the material, credit/d it if you can.
